          "Let's start with what is rising, because there are four skills, and every one of them sounds old fashioned. The first is clear thinking, expressed in plain writing. Here is the truth underneath every AI tool on the market. The output is a mirror of the request. The person who can say exactly what they want owns the result. Let me make that concrete. Two owners ask an AI to write a homepage. The first one types, make me a professional website for my landscaping business. What comes back is wallpaper. Generic green, generic promises, could be any company in any state. The second owner types something different. My customer is a homeowner in a mountain town who just bought five acres and feels in over her head. The first screen needs one sentence that says we handle all of it, one photo of a finished yard, and one button that says get a free walkthrough. Write it warm, plain, eighth grade reading level, no industry jargon. Same tool. But the second owner did the thinking first, and the tool just did the typing. That gap, between the vague ask and the precise ask, is the whole ballgame for the next five years. I have watched an AI agent build a complete working website overnight, and the quality of that site was decided before the agent ever started, in the one page of writing I handed it.",
          "The second rising skill is taste. When production gets cheap, everybody can make ten versions of everything. Somebody still has to know which one is good. Taste is knowing the third draft is flat, the headline is trying too hard, the design looks like everyone else's. Here is what that looks like in practice. I generate product mockups for my apparel company all the time. The machine hands me twelve options in a minute. Eleven of them are fine, and fine is the enemy. My job is to catch the one where the light falls right and the type breathes, and to reject the rest without apology. The machine made twelve. Taste picked the one, and the one is what customers actually see. And you build taste the boring way, by studying excellent work on purpose, every week, and asking why it works.",
